"""
MKT Original Commentary — Proverbs chapters 1–3
Run: python3 scripts/zc-original-proverbs-1-3.py
Key translation decisions:
- māšāl: "proverb" (v1:1); covers riddle, aphorism, discourse, taunt — not just short sayings
- mûsār: "discipline" throughout (not just "instruction") — carries connotation of corrective training
- ḥokmāh: "wisdom" — practical skill for navigating life within covenant order
- yirʾat-YHWH: "fear of the LORD" — the foundational covenant disposition, not mere terror
- rēʾšît: "beginning" (1:7) — both temporal start and qualitative first principle
- ʾiššāh zārāh / nokrîyyāh: "immoral/strange woman" — the adulteress as wisdom's antithesis (ch2)
- ḥesed wĕʾemet: "steadfast love and faithfulness" (3:3) — the Sinai covenant-character pair
- ʾēṣ ḥayyîm: "tree of life" (3:18) — the Gen 2–3 creation motif applied to wisdom
"""

import json, pathlib
ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

new_data = {
    "1": {
        "1": "<p>The book opens with the standard Solomonic attribution formula: &#8220;proverbs of Solomon (<i>miš&lsquo;l&ecirc; Šᵉl&ocirc;m&ocirc;h</i>), son of David, king of Israel.&#8221; The Hebrew <i>māšāl</i> (rendered &#8220;proverb&#8221;) is a broader term than the English suggests — it encompasses short aphorisms, extended discourses, riddles, and taunt songs. The book&#8217;s title thus signals a collection of diverse wisdom forms united by Solomonic sponsorship. The lineage &#8220;son of David&#8221; ties wisdom to the Davidic covenant tradition (1&#160;Kgs&#160;3:3&#8211;14; 4:29&#8211;34).</p>",
        "2": "<p>Verses 2&#8211;6 constitute the prologue: a purpose statement using a series of infinitive constructs. &#8220;Learning (<i>lāda&#703;at</i>) wisdom (<i>ḥokmāh</i>) and discipline (<i>mûsār</i>)&#8221; — the two terms are frequently paired in Proverbs. <i>Ḥokmāh</i> denotes the practical skill of living well within divine order; <i>mûsār</i> carries the sense of corrective training or discipline, not merely instruction. The MKT renders it &#8220;discipline&#8221; consistently to preserve the formative, sometimes painful, quality of the process (cf. 3:11&#8211;12; Heb&#160;12:5).</p>",
        "3": "<p>&#8220;Wise conduct (<i>haśk&ecirc;l</i>)&#8221; translates <i>haśkîl</i>, the hiphil infinitive of <i>śākal</i> — to act prudently, prosper through skillful behavior. The triad &#8220;righteousness (<i>ṣedeq</i>), justice (<i>mišpāṭ</i>), and integrity (<i>mêšārîm</i>)&#8221; appears together as the standard of covenant social order (cf. Deut&#160;16:18&#8211;20; Ps&#160;99:4). The book&#8217;s opening thus grounds practical wisdom in covenant ethics.</p>",
        "4": "<p>&#8220;The naive (<i>peta&#703;îm</i>)&#8221; are those who are not yet hardened in foolishness — the young, the untested, the open (the root <i>pth</i> means &#8220;open, wide&#8221;; susceptible in both directions). &#8220;Shrewdness (<i>&#703;ormāh</i>)&#8221; is savvy discernment — the ability to see through situations — a virtue the serpent possesses (Gen&#160;3:1) but here redeemed by being channeled through wisdom. &#8220;Knowledge (<i>da&#703;at</i>) and discernment (<i>mᵉzimmāh</i>)&#8221; round out the gift to youth.</p>",
        "5": "<p>The prologue turns from the young to the already-wise: wisdom is not only for the naive but for those who already possess it. &#8220;Skill in guidance (<i>taḥbulôt</i>)&#8221; — the nautical metaphor of ropes and steering (from <i>ḥōbel</i>, rope/cable) — refers to the ability to navigate complex situations and provide strategic counsel. It appears in 11:14; 20:18; 24:6 in military and leadership contexts.</p>",
        "6": "<p>&#8220;Enigmas (<i>ḥîdôt</i>)&#8221; are riddles, puzzles — the same word used of Samson&#8217;s riddle (Judg&#160;14:12) and the Queen of Sheba&#8217;s &#8220;hard questions&#8221; (1&#160;Kgs&#160;10:1). Proverbs itself is a collection of compressed wisdom where meaning is not always transparent; understanding proverbs&#8217; &#8220;hidden layer&#8221; is part of the goal. The wise person can move from the surface form to the deeper application.</p>",
        "7": "<p>The programmatic thesis of Proverbs and of the broader wisdom tradition: <i>yir&#702;at-YHWH r&ecirc;&#702;šît da&#702;at</i> — &#8220;fear of the LORD is the beginning of knowledge.&#8221; The term <i>yirʾāh</i> (fear) in the wisdom books is not mere terror but the foundational disposition of the covenant person: reverence, trust, and submission that keeps life properly oriented. <i>R&ecirc;&#702;šît</i> means both &#8220;beginning&#8221; (temporal first) and &#8220;first principle&#8221; (qualitative foundation) — wisdom does not start from neutral reason but from covenant relation. &#8220;Fools (<i>&#702;ewîlîm</i>) despise wisdom and discipline&#8221; — the fool is not the ignorant but the willfully rejecting person.</p>",
        "8": "<p>The main body of chapters 1&#8211;9 begins here with the first &#8220;my son&#8221; address — <i>bᵉnî</i> is the standard didactic address of the wisdom teacher (occurs 15 times in chs.&#160;1&#8211;9). The dual instruction from &#8220;father&#8221; (<i>ʾābîkā</i>) and &#8220;mother&#8221; (<i>ʾimmekā</i>) is notable: both parents&#8217; teaching carries authority (cf. 6:20; 31:1&#8211;9). The word for &#8220;teaching&#8221; here is <i>tôrāh</i> — which can mean instruction broadly or the Torah specifically; the context is parental formation, not yet Mosaic code, though the verbal resonance with Deuteronomy is intentional.</p>",
        "9": "<p>The rewards of parental wisdom are expressed as jewelry and garland — external adornment marking the person who has internalized the teaching. &#8220;A graceful garland (<i>liwyat ḥēn</i>)&#8221; on the head and &#8220;a chain of honor (<i>&#703;ᵃnāqôt</i>)&#8221; around the neck. The image recurs in 4:9 and parallels the garland of honor bestowed on a student by wisdom herself. In a world where social standing was partly expressed through dress and ornament, wisdom&#8217;s adornment marks its bearer as honored.</p>",
        "10": "<p>The first temptation scene begins — the father warns against the seduction of <i>ḥaṭṭāʾîm</i> (sinners, those who miss the mark) who try to &#8220;entice&#8221; (<i>pittîkā</i>, hiphil of <i>pth</i> — the same root as &#8220;naive/open&#8221; in v4). The condensed command &#8220;do not yield (<i>ʾal-tōʾbeh</i>)&#8221; — the jussive negative — draws on the authority of the father&#8217;s voice to create a decisive moment.</p>",
        "11": "<p>The sinners&#8217; speech begins (vv11&#8211;14) — remarkably, the teacher gives voice to the temptation so the student can recognize its shape. The ambush imagery — &#8220;lie in wait (<i>nᵉʾorbāh</i>)&#8221; and &#8220;ambush (<i>niṣpᵉnāh</i>)&#8221; — recalls the language of warfare and predation (cf. Ps&#160;10:8&#8211;9). The phrase &#8220;for no reason (<i>ḥinnām</i>)&#8221; echoes the description of the Satan&#8217;s persecution of Job: &#8220;without reason&#8221; (Job&#160;1:9; 2:3).</p>",
        "12": "<p>&#8220;Swallow them alive like Sheol&#8221; — the sinners invoke the underworld image: Sheol as the insatiable gullet that swallows whole (cf. Num&#160;16:30&#8211;33; Hab&#160;2:5). The comparison &#8220;whole (<i>tᵉmîmîm</i>) like those who descend to the grave (<i>bôr</i>)&#8221; uses <i>tāmîm</i> (complete, whole — the same word as &#8220;blameless&#8221; for Noah and Abraham), ironically: they will swallow the innocent whole, as Sheol swallows the dead.</p>",
        "13": "<p>The appeal to material gain — &#8220;every kind of treasure (<i>hôn yāqār</i>)&#8221; and &#8220;loot (<i>šālāl</i>).&#8221; <i>Šālāl</i> is the technical term for war plunder or spoil; the violence implied is military-scale predation on the innocent. The fantasy of easy riches through violence is the trap&#8217;s bait.</p>",
        "14": "<p>&#8220;Throw in your lot (<i>gôrālᵉkā</i>)&#8221; — a technical term; the <i>gôrāl</i> was the lot cast to divide property or assign duties (cf. Josh&#160;18:6; Prov&#160;16:33). &#8220;A common purse (<i>kîs ʾeḥād</i>)&#8221; — shared funds, suggesting gang solidarity. The appeal is to belonging and communal gain.</p>",
        "15": "<p>The father&#8217;s counter-command uses the journey metaphor central to Proverbs: &#8220;their road (<i>derek</i>) ... their path (<i>nātîb</i>).&#8221; Two different words for path — <i>derek</i> (highway, the main way) and <i>nātîb</i> (bypath, side trail). The father urges separation from the way entirely: &#8220;keep your feet far (<i>mᵉna&#703; ...</i>)&#8221; — do not even get close.</p>",
        "16": "<p>The rationale for avoidance: their feet &#8220;run to evil (<i>rāṣāh lāra&#703;</i>)&#8221; and &#8220;rush (<i>ûyᵉmaharû</i>) to shed blood.&#8221; The double speed — run, rush — marks the eagerness of the wicked for violence. This verse is partially quoted in Isa&#160;59:7 and Rom&#160;3:15, where it describes universal human sin.</p>",
        "17": "<p>An intrusive proverbial aside: &#8220;How futile (<i>kî-ḥinnām</i>) to spread a net in full view (<i>bᵉ&#703;ênê</i> = in the eyes of) of every bird (kol-ba&#703;al kānāp = every master of a wing).&#8221; The crux is interpretive — two main readings: (a) Even a bird knows to avoid a visible net, but sinners are stupider than birds; (b) the sinners&#8217; ambush is as futile as a visible net — the prey (God, justice) sees it. The MKT follows reading (a), with v18&#8211;19 confirming: the sinners are the bird that walks into the net they themselves set.</p>",
        "18": "<p>The reversal: &#8220;they lie in wait for their own blood (<i>dāmām</i>)&#8221; — the same word used of innocent blood in v11. The sinners who planned to shed blood end up shedding their own. The ambush turns back on the ambushers — the poetic justice that Proverbs often exploits.</p>",
        "19": "<p>The moralizing summary: &#8220;everyone who is greedy for unjust gain (<i>bōṣēaʿ bāṣa&#703;</i>)&#8221; — <i>bāṣaʿ</i> (gain, profit, cut off) is consistently negative in wisdom literature; it denotes predatory profit at another&#8217;s expense (cf. 28:16; Isa&#160;56:11; Jer&#160;6:13). &#8220;It costs them their lives (<i>nepeš bᵉʿālāyw yiqqāḥ</i>)&#8221; — literally &#8220;takes the life of its owners.&#8221; <i>Nepeš</i> here is the full self, not merely breath.</p>",
        "20": "<p>Wisdom (<i>Ḥokmôt</i>) now appears as a personified woman crying in public (vv20&#8211;33). <i>Ḥokmôt</i> is a plural form of <i>ḥokmāh</i> — possibly an intensive (&#8220;Wisdom itself&#8221;) or reflecting an older plural-of-majesty usage. Her cry in &#8220;the streets (<i>bāḥûṣ</i>)&#8221; and &#8220;public squares (<i>bārrᵉḥōbôt</i>)&#8221; — the busiest places — contrasts with the hidden ambush of the sinners (v11). Wisdom is not secret but public and insistent.</p>",
        "21": "<p>&#8220;At the head of the busy thoroughfares (<i>bᵉrōʾš hōmiyyôt</i>)&#8221; — literally &#8220;at the head of the noisy streets.&#8221; &#8220;At the gates of the city (<i>šaʿărê qārāʾ&#x2019;)&#8221; — the gate was the city&#8217;s judicial and commercial center, the place where all civic life was transacted (cf. Ruth&#160;4:1; Amos&#160;5:10&#8211;15). Wisdom speaks where power is exercised and decisions are made.</p>",
        "22": "<p>Wisdom&#8217;s opening question addresses three types: &#8220;the naive (<i>pᵉtāyîm</i>)&#8221; (open to wisdom or to folly — morally undetermined), &#8220;scoffers (<i>lēṣîm</i>)&#8221; (the intensely mocking, actively hostile to wisdom — a key Proverbs type), and &#8220;fools (<i>kᵉsîlîm</i>)&#8221; (the thick-skulled, the complacent). The three represent a spectrum from potentially reachable to probably hardened.</p>",
        "23": "<p>&#8220;Turn back at my rebuke (<i>tāšûbû lᵉtôkaḥtî</i>)&#8221; — <i>šûb</i> (turn, return) is the standard repentance word; wisdom uses it. The promise: &#8220;I will pour out (<i>ʾabbîʿāh</i>) my spirit (<i>rûḥî</i>) to you.&#8221; <i>Nābî&#702;</i> (the root of <i>ʾabbîʿāh</i>) means to spring up, bubble over (cf. Ps&#160;19:2; 119:171). The outpouring of wisdom&#8217;s <i>rûaḥ</i> echoes later prophetic promises of the divine Spirit (Isa&#160;44:3; Ezek&#160;36:27; Joel&#160;2:28).</p>",
        "24": "<p>The hinge verse — Wisdom&#8217;s call was rejected (past tense in Hebrew): &#8220;I called (<i>qārāʾtî</i>)&#8221; and &#8220;I stretched out my hand (<i>nāṭîtî yādî</i>).&#8221; The outstretched hand is the gesture of divine invitation and prophetic summons (Isa&#160;65:2; 66:4). The rejection has already occurred; the consequences follow.</p>",
        "25": "<p>Three parallel rejections: &#8220;you rejected (<i>tiprᵉʿû</i>) all my advice,&#8221; &#8220;you would accept none of my correction (<i>tôkaḥtî</i>).&#8221; <i>Pāra&#703;</i> (to let loose, reject, disregard) is used of Israel&#8217;s rejection of God in Exod&#160;32:25; the moral recklessness of &#8220;letting go&#8221; of all restraint. The refusal of <i>tôkaḥat</i> (correction, reproof) is the defining marker of the fool throughout Proverbs (9:7&#8211;8; 12:1; 15:10).</p>",
        "26": "<p>Wisdom&#8217;s terrifying reversal: &#8220;I will laugh (<i>ʾeśḥaq</i>) at your calamity (<i>bᵉʾêdkem</i>); I will mock (<i>ʾel&#702;ag</i>) when terror (<i>paḥadkem</i>) strikes.&#8221; God himself is said to laugh at the wicked in Ps&#160;2:4; 37:13; 59:8 — the sovereign irony of the one rejected. The terms <i>ʾêd</i> (calamity, ruin) and <i>paḥad</i> (sudden terror) appear again in the disaster lists of Job and the prophets.</p>",
        "27": "<p>The disaster imagery — &#8220;like a storm (<i>kᵉsûpāh</i>)&#8221; and &#8220;like a whirlwind (<i>sᵉʿārāh</i>)&#8221; — is standard prophetic language for divine judgment (Isa&#160;29:6; Nah&#160;1:3; Job&#160;38:1). The pairing of <i>ṣārāh</i> (distress, trouble — the standard affliction word) and <i>ṣûqāh</i> (anguish, straits) underscores the total encompassing of the disaster.</p>",
        "28": "<p>The reversal of v23: &#8220;then they will call (<i>yiqrāʾûnnî</i>) on me but I will not answer.&#8221; The same verb as wisdom&#8217;s call in v24 — now reversed: the rejectors call, but wisdom does not answer. The motif of unanswered prayer in judgment contexts appears in Mic&#160;3:4; Jer&#160;11:11&#8211;12; Lam&#160;3:44.</p>",
        "29": "<p>The reason given for wisdom&#8217;s withdrawal: &#8220;they hated (<i>śānᵉʾû</i>) knowledge (<i>da&#703;at</i>) and did not choose (<i>lōʾ bāḥărû</i>) to fear the LORD.&#8221; <i>Bāḥar</i> (to choose, elect) is used of God&#8217;s election of Israel (Deut&#160;7:6) and of human moral choice (Deut&#160;30:19). Rejecting wisdom&#8217;s instruction is characterized as an act of will, not ignorance.</p>",
        "30": "<p>&#8220;They wanted none of my advice (<i>lōʾ-ʾābû lᵉ&#703;ᵉṣātî</i>)&#8221; — the verb <i>ʾābāh</i> (to be willing, to consent) appears in Deuteronomy&#8217;s covenant lawsuit texts (Deut&#160;1:26; 9:23; Isa&#160;1:19&#8211;20). The rejection is one of consent, not capacity — they were capable of choosing but refused.</p>",
        "31": "<p>The retributive principle expressed as eating: &#8220;they will eat the fruit of their own path (<i>yōkᵉlû mippᵉrî darkām</i>).&#8221; The <i>derek</i> (way, path) produces fruit — the moral-agricultural metaphor connects actions to consequences organically (cf. Gal&#160;6:7&#8211;8). &#8220;Gorged on their own schemes (<i>mimoʿaṣôtêhem yiśbāʾû</i>)&#8221; — <i>śābēaʿ</i> (to be sated, filled to excess) captures the bitter irony of getting exactly what they planned.</p>",
        "32": "<p>&#8220;The waywardness (<i>mᵉšûbāh</i>) of the naive will kill them&#8221; — <i>mᵉšûbāh</i> is the noun form of <i>šûb</i> (to turn), meaning &#8220;turning away, apostasy, waywardness&#8221; — the same root as repentance but in the opposite direction (cf. Jer&#160;2:19; Hos&#160;14:4). &#8220;The complacency (<i>šalwāh</i>) of fools&#8221; — <i>šalwāh</i> means ease, prosperity, false security — the fool&#8217;s fatal contentment with their current state.</p>",
        "33": "<p>The closing promise seals the speech: &#8220;whoever listens to me will live in security (<i>yiškon-beṭaḥ</i>).&#8221; <i>Bāṭaḥ</i> (to be secure, trust) is a covenantal security word: the land promised to the patriarchs is to be inhabited &#8220;in security&#8221; (Lev&#160;26:5; Deut&#160;12:10; Jer&#160;23:6). &#8220;Free from the dread (<i>paḥad</i>) of harm (<i>rāʿāh</i>)&#8221; — the <i>paḥad</i> that fell on fools (v26) is absent for wisdom&#8217;s followers. Security is the fruit of listening, not the default condition.</p>"
    },
    "2": {
        "1": "<p>Chapter 2 is a single extended sentence in Hebrew — the longest in Proverbs — with a conditional structure: if (vv1&#8211;4) → then (vv5&#8211;11) → to deliver from (vv12&#8211;19) → so that (vv20&#8211;22). &#8220;Accept (<i>tiqqaḥ</i>) my words&#8221; and &#8220;store up (<i>tiṣpōn</i>) my commands&#8221; — <i>ṣāpan</i> (to hide, store, treasure) indicates active hoarding of the teaching, not passive reception (cf. 7:1; Ps&#160;119:11).</p>",
        "2": "<p>&#8220;Turning your ear (<i>haqšîb ʾoznᵉkā</i>)&#8221; — the hiphil of <i>qāšab</i> is to give careful, attentive listening (cf. 4:20; Ps&#160;10:17). &#8220;Directing your heart (<i>tаṭṭeh libbᵉkā</i>)&#8221; — the heart (<i>lēb</i>) in Hebrew anthropology is the seat of will, understanding, and decision — not merely emotion. The ear hears; the heart internalizes and acts.</p>",
        "3": "<p>The imperative &#8220;call out (<i>tiqrāʾ</i>)&#8221; for discernment and &#8220;cry aloud (<i>titten qôlekā</i>) for understanding&#8221; — the same verbs used of wisdom&#8217;s public call in 1:20&#8211;21. Now the student is urged to call for wisdom as wisdom called to the student. The symmetry is deliberate: wisdom cries in the street; the seeker must cry back in prayer.</p>",
        "4": "<p>The treasure-hunting similes: &#8220;search for it like silver (<i>kakkᵉsep</i>)&#8221; and &#8220;dig for it like buried treasure (<i>kammᵃṭmônîm</i>).&#8221; Silver was the primary monetary metal in the ANE; buried treasure was found through persistent searching. The two images escalate: seeking as commerce → seeking as excavation. The same silver-seeker image recurs in 3:14 and 8:10&#8211;11 where wisdom&#8217;s value exceeds silver.</p>",
        "5": "<p>The first &#8220;then (<i>ʾāz</i>)&#8221; clause: understanding of <i>yirʾat-YHWH</i> (fear of the LORD — the same phrase as 1:7) and <i>daʿat ʾĕlōhîm</i> (knowledge of God) are the paired result of the diligent search. The two expressions are near-synonyms here: both name the foundational covenant relationship. &#8220;Knowledge of God&#8221; (<i>daʿat ʾĕlōhîm</i>) is a key prophetic phrase (Hos&#160;4:1&#8211;2; 6:6) — not just information about God but relational knowing through covenant faithfulness.</p>",
        "6": "<p>The theological underpinning of the search: &#8220;the LORD gives wisdom (<i>yitten ḥokmāh</i>).&#8221; Despite the vigorous human seeking of vv1&#8211;4, wisdom is ultimately divine gift, not human achievement (cf. 1&#160;Kgs&#160;3:12; Job&#160;28:23&#8211;28). &#8220;From his mouth (<i>mippîhû</i>) flow knowledge and understanding&#8221; — wisdom is the speech of God, his verbal self-disclosure (cf. 8:22&#8211;31).</p>",
        "7": "<p>&#8220;He stores up (<i>yiṣpōn</i>) proven wisdom (<i>tûšîyyāh</i>) for the upright (<i>layyᵉšārîm</i>).&#8221; <i>Tûšîyyāh</i> is a difficult wisdom term: &#8220;sound wisdom, effectiveness, abiding success&#8221; — the real working out of wisdom in life (cf. 3:21; 8:14; Job&#160;5:12; 6:13). The same root <i>ṣāpan</i> (to store/hide) used of the seeker in v1 is now used of God — both seek and store. &#8220;Shield (<i>māgēn</i>)&#8221; for the upright — God&#8217;s protection is expressed in military imagery (cf. Gen&#160;15:1; Ps&#160;3:3).</p>",
        "8": "<p>&#8220;He guards (<i>nōṣēr</i>) the paths of justice&#8221; — the participle form suggests ongoing action. <i>Nāṣar</i> (to guard, watch, keep) is the same root as the divine attribute &#8220;keeping steadfast love&#8221; (Exod&#160;34:7) and the word for the &#8220;keeper&#8221; in Ps&#160;121. &#8220;Those who are faithful (<i>ḥᵃsîdāyw</i>) to him&#8221; — the <i>ḥāsîd</i> (covenant-loyal one, &#8220;godly&#8221;) are those who embody <i>ḥesed</i> in response to God&#8217;s <i>ḥesed</i>.</p>",
        "9": "<p>The second &#8220;then&#8221; clause: &#8220;you will understand what is right (<i>ṣedeq</i>) and just (<i>mišpāṭ</i>) and fair (<i>mêšārîm</i>) — every good way of living (<i>kol-maʿgal-ṭôb</i>).&#8221; The three-term ethical triad of 1:3 recurs, now as the consequence of pursuing wisdom. The &#8220;way of living&#8221; (<i>maʿgal</i> = the track made by a wheel, a well-worn path) appears again in 4:11; 5:6&#8211;21.</p>",
        "10": "<p>&#8220;Wisdom will enter (<i>tābôʾ</i>) your heart (<i>bᵉlibbᵉkā</i>)&#8221; — the movement is from the outside (teaching, speech) to the inside (heart, will). &#8220;Knowledge (<i>da&#703;at</i>) will delight (<i>yinʿam</i>) your inner being (<i>napsᵉkā</i>).&#8221; <i>Nāʿēm</i> (to be pleasant, delightful) — wisdom becomes not an imposed duty but an internalized delight; the word recurs in 9:17 and Ps&#160;133:1.</p>",
        "11": "<p>&#8220;Discretion (<i>mᵉzimmāh</i>) will watch over you; understanding (<i>tᵉbûnāh</i>) will protect you.&#8221; <i>Mᵉzimmāh</i> (discretion, strategic thinking — the ability to plan wisely; cf. 1:4; 5:2) and <i>tᵉbûnāh</i> (understanding as the faculty that perceives underlying patterns) are now personified as guardian figures. The wisdom that was sought becomes the protector of the seeker.</p>",
        "12": "<p>&#8220;Delivering you (<i>lᵉhaṣṣîlᵉkā</i>) from the path of evil (<i>derek rāʿ</i>)&#8221; — <i>nāṣal</i> (hiphil: to rescue, deliver) is a deliverance verb (cf. Exod&#160;3:8; 18:4; Ps&#160;18:17). &#8220;From those who speak twisted things (<i>miʾîš mᵉdabbēr tahpukôt</i>)&#8221; — <i>tahpukôt</i> (perversions, inversions, upside-down speech) names speech that reverses the moral order (cf. 6:14; 8:13; Deut&#160;32:20).</p>",
        "13": "<p>&#8220;Who abandon the straight paths (<i>ʾorḥôt yōšer</i>) and choose to walk in darkness.&#8221; <i>Yōšer</i> (straightness, uprightness) and darkness are the standard two-way framework of Proverbs: the way of wisdom is light and straightness; the way of folly is crooked and dark. The choice to walk in darkness is a volitional act — &#8220;choose (<i>lāleket</i>)&#8221; — not an accident.</p>",
        "14": "<p>&#8220;Who take pleasure (<i>śᵉmēḥîm</i>) in evil (<i>laʿᵃśôt rāʿ</i>) and celebrate (<i>yāgîlû</i>) every kind of wrongdoing.&#8221; The intensification here is crucial: these are not reluctant sinners but those who find joy in evil. The same vocabulary of rejoicing (śimḥāh, gîl) that describes worship of God is here applied to evil — a perverse inversion of the proper orientation of delight.</p>",
        "15": "<p>&#8220;Their ways (<i>ʾorḥōtêhem</i>) are crooked (<i>ʿiqqᵉšîm</i>) and their paths (<i>nᵉtîbôtām</i>) are twisted (<i>nᵉlôzîm</i>).&#8221; Three different Hebrew words for path are used in this section — <i>derek, maʿgal, ʾōraḥ, nātîb</i> — Proverbs&#8217; path vocabulary is remarkably rich. <i>ʿIqqēš</i> (crooked, perverse — from a root meaning to twist) and <i>lûz</i> (to turn aside, deviate) both describe moral deviation from the straight path.</p>",
        "16": "<p>The second deliverer: wisdom saves from &#8220;the immoral woman (<i>ʾiššāh zārāh</i>) — the seductive stranger (<i>nāk­rîyyāh</i>) with smooth words (<i>ʾᵃmārêhā heḥᵉlîqāh</i>).&#8221; <i>Zārāh</i> (strange, foreign) and <i>nokrîyyāh</i> (foreign woman, outsider) may describe a literal foreign woman, a cult prostitute, or simply the adulteress who has placed herself outside the covenant community. The moral category of &#8220;outside&#8221; is more important than ethnicity. <i>Ḥālaq</i> (smooth) describes the flattering, slippery speech of seduction (cf. 5:3; 6:24; Ps&#160;55:21).</p>",
        "17": "<p>&#8220;She has abandoned (<i>ʿāzᵉbāh</i>) the partner (<i>ʾallûp</i>) of her youth (<i>nᵉʿûrêhā</i>)&#8221; — <i>ʾallûp</i> (intimate companion, close friend) is a rare but intense term for a covenant partner. &#8220;The covenant she made before God (<i>bᵉrît ʾĕlōhêhā</i>)&#8221; — this is almost certainly the marriage covenant witnessed by God (cf. Mal&#160;2:14 where marriage is explicitly called a <i>bᵉrît</i> with YHWH as witness). The woman&#8217;s sin is not merely sexual but covenantal.</p>",
        "18": "<p>&#8220;Her house leads down to death (<i>mōwet</i>); her paths go to the spirits of the dead (<i>rᵉpāʾîm</i>).&#8221; <i>Rᵉpāʾîm</i> are the shades of the dead, the weak and powerless inhabitants of Sheol (cf. Isa&#160;14:9; 26:14; Ps&#160;88:10). The adulteress&#8217;s house is a gateway to Sheol — the path of sexual transgression ends in the underworld. The contrast with wisdom (2:20&#8211;22: land, dwelling, life) is stark.</p>",
        "19": "<p>&#8220;None who enter her house return (<i>lōʾ yᵉšûbûn</i>); they never find their way back to the paths of life (<i>ʾorḥôt ḥayyîm</i>).&#8221; The finality is emphatic — there is no return from this path. The contrast with v12&#8211;15 is precise: those paths are twisted and crooked; the paths of life are the alternative wisdom provides. The irreversibility echoes Sheol imagery: those who descend do not return (Job&#160;7:9; 10:21).</p>",
        "20": "<p>&#8220;All this so that (<i>lᵉmaʿan</i>) you will walk in the path of the good (<i>derek ṭôbîm</i>)&#8221; — the purpose clause gathers the entire chapter&#8217;s protection toward a positive end. The double &#8220;path of the good&#8221; and &#8220;road of the righteous (<i>ʾorḥôt ṣaddîqîm</i>)&#8221; forms a positive endpoint that mirrors the book&#8217;s opening concern (1:3).</p>",
        "21": "<p>&#8220;The righteous (<i>yᵉšārîm</i>) will live in the land (<i>yišᵉkᵉnû-ʾāreṣ</i>)&#8221; — the land-inheritance promise of Deuteronomy (Deut&#160;11:8&#8211;9; Ps&#160;37:9&#8211;11, 29) applied to personal wisdom. &#8220;Those of integrity (<i>tᵉmîmîm</i>) will remain (<i>yiwwātᵉrû</i>) in it&#8221; — <i>tāmîm</i> (complete, blameless, whole) is the covenant-integrity term (Gen&#160;6:9 for Noah; Gen&#160;17:1 for Abraham). Land-inheritance is the covenant outcome of righteous living.</p>",
        "22": "<p>The counterpart: &#8220;the wicked (<i>rᵉšāʿîm</i>) will be cut off (<i>yikkārētû</i>) from the land, and the unfaithful (<i>bôgᵉdîm</i>) will be uprooted (<i>yissᵉḥû</i>) from it.&#8221; <i>Kārat</i> (cut off) is a covenantal punishment term — &#8220;cut off from the people&#8221; appears throughout Leviticus for covenant violations (Lev&#160;7:20&#8211;21; 18:29). <i>Bôgēd</i> (the treacherous, the faithless covenant-breaker) provides the ethical antonym to <i>tāmîm</i>. The chapter ends with creation-level consequences.</p>"
    },
    "3": {
        "1": "<p>Chapter 3 returns to the direct &#8220;my son (<i>bᵉnî</i>)&#8221; address (cf. 1:8; 2:1). &#8220;My instruction (<i>tôrātî</i>)&#8221; — <i>tôrāh</i> here is parental teaching, but the word is the same as the Mosaic Torah; the wisdom teacher&#8217;s instruction participates in the same authority structure. &#8220;Let your heart hold on (<i>yiṣṣōr</i>) to my commands&#8221; — <i>nāṣar</i> (to guard, keep carefully) is the same verb used of God&#8217;s keeping steadfast love (Exod&#160;34:7) and the Psalmist keeping the law (Ps&#160;119:2).</p>",
        "2": "<p>&#8220;They will add to you a long life (<i>ʾōrek yāmîm</i>), many years of living (<i>šᵉnôt ḥayyîm</i>), and peace (<i>šālôm</i>).&#8221; Long life and peace are the standard covenant-blessing terms: <i>ʾōrek yāmîm</i> appears in the Aaronic blessing-promise context (Ps&#160;21:4; 23:6); <i>šālôm</i> is the comprehensive covenant wellbeing (completeness, flourishing, not just absence of conflict). These are the outcomes of wisdom that motivate the son to listen.</p>",
        "3": "<p>&#8220;Let steadfast love (<i>ḥesed</i>) and faithfulness (<i>ʾĕmet</i>) never leave you.&#8221; The paired covenant attributes <i>ḥesed wĕʾĕmet</i> are the core description of YHWH&#8217;s character at Sinai (Exod&#160;34:6&#8211;7) and appear throughout the Psalms (Ps&#160;25:10; 40:10&#8211;11; 85:10). The student is called to embody the divine character. &#8220;Wear them like a necklace (<i>qašrēm &#702;al-gargᵉrōtekā</i>)&#8221; — bind them on your throat (cf. 1:9; 6:21; Deut&#160;6:8). &#8220;Inscribe them on your heart (<i>kātᵉbēm &#702;al-lûaḥ libbekā</i>)&#8221; — the language of Deut&#160;6:6 (&#8220;these words... shall be on your heart&#8221;) and Jer&#160;31:33 (the new covenant written on hearts).</p>",
        "4": "<p>&#8220;You will find favor (<i>ḥēn</i>) and a good reputation (<i>śēkel-ṭôb</i>) in the eyes of God and people (<i>bᵉʿênê ʾĕlōhîm wᵉʾādām</i>).&#8221; The dual approval — divine and human — recurs in describing Joseph (Gen&#160;39:3&#8211;4, 21), Samuel (1&#160;Sam&#160;2:26), and Jesus (Luke&#160;2:52). <i>Śēkel</i> (prudence, good sense, insight) is the practical wisdom that makes one well-regarded (cf. 1&#160;Sam&#160;25:3).</p>",
        "5": "<p>&#8220;Trust in the LORD (<i>beṭaḥ ʾel-YHWH</i>) with all your heart (<i>bᵉkol-libbekā</i>).&#8221; One of the most cited verses in Proverbs. <i>Bāṭaḥ</i> (to trust, be secure) is a covenantal security term (cf. 1:33; Ps&#160;22:4&#8211;5; Isa&#160;26:3&#8211;4). &#8220;Do not depend on your own insight (<i>ʾal-tiššāʿēn ʾel-bînātekā</i>)&#8221; — <i>šāʿan</i> (to lean on, rely on) occurs with negative force in Isa&#160;31:1 (&#8220;who rely on horses&#8221;) and Ezek&#160;29:7. The contrast is not between reason and faith but between self-sufficient reasoning and God-dependent wisdom.</p>",
        "6": "<p>&#8220;Acknowledge him (<i>dāʿēhû</i>) in everything you do (<i>bᵉkol-dᵉrākekā</i>), and he will direct your steps (<i>yᵉyaššēr ʾorḥōtekā</i>).&#8221; <i>Yāda&#702;</i> (to know) here is covenantal knowing — to acknowledge, reckon with, give full weight to (cf. 1&#160;Sam&#160;2:12; Hos&#160;4:1). The promise is that God will &#8220;make straight (<i>yāšar</i>, piel)&#8221; the paths — removing obstacles, straightening the crooked way.</p>",
        "7": "<p>&#8220;Do not think of yourself as wise in your own eyes (<i>ʾal-tᵉhî ḥākām bᵉʿênekā</i>).&#8221; The precise phrasing recurs in 26:12 (&#8220;do you see a person wise in their own eyes? There is more hope for a fool&#8221;) and Isa&#160;5:21 (&#8220;woe to those who are wise in their own eyes&#8221;). Self-assessed wisdom is the root of arrogant folly. &#8220;Fear the LORD and turn from evil&#8221; — the same pairing as the programmatic verse (1:7 + 3:7b) grounds the ethical turn in covenant piety.</p>",
        "8": "<p>&#8220;This will bring health (<i>rip&#702;ût</i>) to your whole body (<i>lᵉšârekkā</i>) and strength (<i>šiqwî</i>) to your bones.&#8221; <i>Šōr</i> (navel, or possibly the body&#8217;s whole frame — the word is rare) is sometimes translated &#8220;navel&#8221; or &#8220;body.&#8221; <i>Šiqwî</i> is also rare — &#8220;refreshment, moisture&#8221; — suggesting the bones being moistened rather than dry (cf. Prov&#160;17:22; Job&#160;21:24). The physical dimension of wisdom&#8217;s blessings is consistent throughout Proverbs: wisdom is embodied.</p>",
        "9": "<p>&#8220;Honor the LORD with your wealth (<i>hôn</i>)&#8221; and &#8220;the first portion (<i>rēʾšît</i>) of all you produce.&#8221; <i>Rēʾšît</i> (firstfruits, best portion — the same word as &#8220;beginning&#8221; in 1:7) links wisdom&#8217;s foundation to the concrete act of giving God the first and best of one&#8217;s produce. The firstfruits legislation (Exod&#160;23:19; Deut&#160;26:1&#8211;11) is here applied to income broadly: the principle generalizes beyond agriculture.</p>",
        "10": "<p>&#8220;Your barns (<i>ʾᵃsāmekā</i>) will overflow with abundance (<i>šābāʿ</i>) and your wine vats (<i>yᵉqābêkā</i>) will brim with new wine (<i>tîrôš</i>).&#8221; The agricultural blessing-language of Deuteronomy (Deut&#160;28:8; Mal&#160;3:10) — full storehouses and overflowing wine vats as the material expression of divine favor. <i>Tîrôš</i> is the fresh-pressed grape juice / must, one of the grain-wine-oil triad of covenant prosperity.</p>",
        "11": "<p>&#8220;Do not reject (<i>ʾal-timʾas</i>) the LORD&#8217;s discipline (<i>mûsar-YHWH</i>)&#8221; and &#8220;do not resent (<i>wᵉʾal-tāqōṣ</i>) his correction (<i>tôkaḥtô</i>).&#8221; The strong imperatives guard against two reactions to hardship: rejecting (treating as contemptible) and resenting (feeling weary and disgusted — <i>qûṣ</i> means to feel loathing, cf. Gen&#160;27:46; Exod&#160;1:12). Discipline and correction are not signs of divine rejection but of divine engagement.</p>",
        "12": "<p>&#8220;For the LORD corrects (<i>yôkîaḥ</i>) those he loves (<i>yᵉʾāhab</i>), just as a father disciplines the son he takes delight in (<i>yirṣeh</i>).&#8221; <i>Yakach</i> (hiphil: to reprove, correct, argue a case) carries a forensic dimension — it is the word for presenting evidence and making one accountable (cf. Job&#160;9:33; 16:21; Isa&#160;2:4). God&#8217;s correction is the action of a parent who takes pleasure (<i>rāṣāh</i>) in the son&#8217;s flourishing. This verse is directly quoted in Heb&#160;12:6.</p>",
        "13": "<p>&#8220;How happy (<i>ʾašrê</i>) is the person who finds wisdom (<i>māṣāʾ ḥokmāh</i>), the one who gains understanding (<i>yāpîq tᵉbûnāh</i>).&#8221; The <i>ʾašrê</i> (beatitude) formula — &#8220;O the happiness of the one who...&#8221; — is used extensively in Psalms (Ps&#160;1:1; 2:12; 34:8) and opens the Sermon on the Mount (Matt&#160;5:3&#8211;11). It is exclamatory, not conditional — declaring the blessed state of the one who already possesses wisdom.</p>",
        "14": "<p>&#8220;Her return (<i>sāḥrāh</i>) is better than the return on silver (<i>kesef</i>), and her profit (<i>tᵉbûʾātāh</i>) better than fine gold (<i>ḥārûṣ</i>).&#8221; <i>Sāḥar</i> is trading, commerce — wisdom measured as a return on investment. <i>Ḥārûṣ</i> (fine, mined gold) is the most refined and valuable metal, the standard of ultimate value (cf. Ps&#160;19:10; Prov&#160;8:10&#8211;11). The merchant-language deliberately transposes wisdom into economic categories to communicate her surpassing value.</p>",
        "15": "<p>&#8220;She is more valuable than precious gems (<i>mippᵉnînîm</i>).&#8221; <i>Pᵉnînîm</i> (probably rubies or corals — the exact stone is debated) represents the most precious of luxury goods. &#8220;Nothing you could want (<i>kol-ḥᵃpāṣekā</i>) measures up to her.&#8221; <i>Ḥāpēṣ</i> (to delight in, desire) — the strongest human wanting. The verse recurs almost verbatim in 8:11 in Wisdom&#8217;s self-speech.</p>",
        "16": "<p>&#8220;In her right hand is long life (<i>ʾōrek yāmîm</i>); in her left hand are wealth (<i>ʿōšer</i>) and honor (<i>kābôd</i>).&#8221; The two-handed image is a visual anthropomorphism: wisdom as a figure who holds gifts. The right hand held the greater gift in OT symbolism (Gen&#160;48:14; Ps&#160;110:1). Long life ranks above wealth and honor — wisdom&#8217;s hierarchy of values. All three are explicitly the gifts Solomon received for asking wisdom rather than wealth (1&#160;Kgs&#160;3:11&#8211;14).</p>",
        "17": "<p>&#8220;Her ways (<i>dᵉrākêhā</i>) are pleasant (<i>dᵉrākê-nōʿam</i>) and all her paths (<i>nᵉtîbôtêhā</i>) lead to peace (<i>šālôm</i>).&#8221; <i>Nōʿam</i> (pleasantness, loveliness, delightfulness — root of the name Naomi, Ruth&#160;1:20) characterizes wisdom&#8217;s way as intrinsically good to travel. <i>Šālôm</i> (comprehensive wellbeing) is the destination, not just the absence of conflict. The paths of wisdom are categorically different from the twisted paths of the wicked (2:13&#8211;15).</p>",
        "18": "<p>&#8220;She is a tree of life (<i>ʿēṣ ḥayyîm</i>) to those who grasp her.&#8221; The <i>ʿēṣ ḥayyîm</i> (tree of life) recalls Gen&#160;2:9; 3:22&#8211;24 — the source of immortality from which humanity was cut off after the fall. Proverbs applies the image to wisdom: she restores access to what sin forfeited. The tree of life recurs in 11:30; 13:12; 15:4 and finally in Rev&#160;22:2. &#8220;Those who hold on to her (<i>tōmᵉkêhā</i>) are called blessed (<i>mᵉʾuššār</i>)&#8221; — the participle of the beatitude-root.</p>",
        "19": "<p>&#8220;By wisdom (<i>bᵉḥokmāh</i>) the LORD laid the foundation (<i>yāsad</i>) of the earth; by understanding (<i>bîn</i>) he set the heavens in place.&#8221; The cosmological grounding of wisdom: it was the instrument of creation (cf. 8:22&#8211;31; Job&#160;28:23&#8211;27; Ps&#160;104:24). The same three wisdom-terms — ḥokmāh, tᵉbûnāh, daʿat — appear in vv19&#8211;20 as the tools of creation, tying the student&#8217;s pursuit of wisdom to participation in the order built into creation itself.</p>",
        "20": "<p>&#8220;Through his knowledge (<i>bᵉdaʿtô</i>) the deep waters (<i>tᵉhōmôt</i>) opened up and the clouds let fall their dew (<i>ʾᵃbāpîm yirᵃʿᵃpû-ṭāl</i>).&#8221; <i>Tᵉhôm</i> (the deep, the primeval ocean) is the chaos-water of Gen&#160;1:2 that God separated at creation. The &#8220;falling of dew&#8221; may allude to the second-day separation of waters and the natural water cycle. Creation is the domain of the wisdom the student is being invited to pursue.</p>",
        "21": "<p>&#8220;My son, keep these in view (<i>ʾal-yālûzû mêʿênekā</i> = do not let them escape from your eyes); hold on to sound wisdom (<i>tûšîyyāh</i>) and discernment (<i>mᵉzimmāh</i>).&#8221; <i>Lûz</i> (to turn aside, deviate — as in 2:15) is used negatively: do not let the teaching deviate from your sight. <i>Tûšîyyāh</i> (sound, effective wisdom — 2:7) and <i>mᵉzimmāh</i> (prudent planning — 2:11) return from ch2 to form a bracket.</p>",
        "22": "<p>&#8220;They will bring life (<i>ḥayyîm</i>) to your soul (<i>napsᵉkā</i>) and beauty (<i>ḥēn</i>) to your neck.&#8221; The same jewelry-and-garland imagery as 1:9; beauty to the neck denotes social honor. <i>Nepeš</i> (throat, soul, self) is where life is centered; wisdom gives life to the whole person.</p>",
        "23": "<p>&#8220;Then you will go on your way (<i>derkᵉkā</i>) in security (<i>lābeṭaḥ</i>), without stumbling (<i>wᵉraglᵉkā lōʾ-tāgôp</i>).&#8221; The journey-security promise — the way (<i>derek</i>) is safe for the wisdom-keeper. <i>Nāgap</i> (to stumble, trip) is used of military defeat and stumbling over obstacles (Ps&#160;91:12; Isa&#160;8:14). The protected path is the opposite of the crooked paths of ch2.</p>",
        "24": "<p>&#8220;When you lie down (<i>tiškeab</i>), you will not be afraid (<i>lōʾ-tîrāʾ</i>); your sleep (<i>šᵉnātekā</i>) will be peaceful (<i>wᵉʿārebāh</i>).&#8221; Peaceful sleep as the sign of security appears also in Ps&#160;4:8; Lev&#160;26:6 (the covenant-blessing land where &#8220;you will lie down with no one to make you afraid&#8221;). <i>ʿāreb</i> (pleasant, sweet) — the taste of undisturbed rest that only comes with cleared conscience and divine protection.</p>",
        "25": "<p>&#8220;Do not fear sudden catastrophe (<i>paḥad pittʾōm</i>) or the destruction (<i>šōʾāh</i>) that falls on the wicked.&#8221; <i>Paḥad pittʾōm</i> (sudden dread) is the unexpected disaster that cannot be planned against (cf. Ps&#160;91:5; Job&#160;22:10). <i>Šōʾāh</i> (desolation, wasteland — from a root meaning to be devastated) is the most complete destruction-word in Hebrew, used of the cosmic judgment in Zeph&#160;1:15. The righteous need not fear what overtakes the wicked.</p>",
        "26": "<p>&#8220;For the LORD will be your security (<i>ûbᵉkîslᵉkā</i>)&#8221; — literally &#8220;and in your side/hip will be the LORD&#8221; — <i>kesil</i> (hip, side, confidence; cf. Job&#160;31:24 where it means &#8220;confidence&#8221;). &#8220;He will keep your foot (<i>raglᵉkā</i>) from every snare (<i>milhāqed</i>).&#8221; The LORD as the guardian of the foot is the language of Ps&#160;121:3; 91:12. The snare (<i>mōqēš</i> variant: <i>milhāqed</i> = trap/net) is the enemy&#8217;s hidden trap.</p>",
        "27": "<p>&#8220;Do not withhold (<i>ʾal-timnaʿ</i>) good (<i>ṭôb</i>) from those who deserve it (<i>mibbᵉʿālāyw</i> = from its owners)&#8221; — <i>baʿal</i> (owner, master) applied to &#8220;good&#8221;: those to whom good-doing properly belongs as their due. The ethical demand now turns outward to neighbor ethics. &#8220;When you have the ability (<i>bᵉhyôt lᵉʾēl yādᵉkā</i> = when it is in the power of your hand)&#8221; — the qualification is not ability but will.</p>",
        "28": "<p>&#8220;Do not tell your neighbor, &#8216;Come back later — I&#8217;ll help you tomorrow,&#8217; when you can help now (<i>wᵉyēš-ʾittāk</i> = and it is with you).&#8221; The deferral-of-good is its own form of withholding. The neighbor (<i>rēaʿ</i>) is the one with whom you share life and community. The command presupposes the capacity to help — the sin is procrastination, not poverty. Jas&#160;2:15&#8211;16 applies this principle to the Christian community.</p>",
        "29": "<p>&#8220;Do not plot (<i>tāḥarōš</i>) harm (<i>rāʿāh</i>) against your neighbor, who lives beside you in trust (<i>lābeṭaḥ</i>).&#8221; <i>Ḥāraš</i> (to plow, devise, plot — Ps&#160;10:2; Mic&#160;2:1) — the agricultural metaphor of plowing transferred to the deliberate scheming of harm. &#8220;Who lives beside you in trust (<i>bōṭēaḥ</i>)&#8221; — the neighbor&#8217;s security (bāṭaḥ) is based on trust; plotting destroys the social fabric of the community built on that trust.</p>",
        "30": "<p>&#8220;Do not pick a fight (<i>ʾal-tārîb</i>) without cause (<i>ḥinnām</i>) with someone who has done you no harm (<i>lōʾ-gᵉmālaʿkā rāʿāh</i>).&#8221; <i>Rîb</i> (lawsuit, quarrel, legal dispute) — the legal register: do not open a case against someone without grounds. <i>Ḥinnām</i> (for nothing, without cause) — the gratuitous quality of the aggression. The repeated use of <i>ḥinnām</i> (also in 1:11) marks unmotivated harm as particularly condemned.</p>",
        "31": "<p>&#8220;Do not envy (<i>qannēʾ</i>) the violent person (<i>ʾîš ḥāmās</i>) or choose to follow any of his paths.&#8221; <i>Qānāʾ</i> (to be jealous, zealously desire — root of the divine epithet <i>ʾēl qannāʾ</i>, jealous God, Exod&#160;20:5) — the covenantal emotion of jealousy / zeal turned toward the violent person&#8217;s apparent success. <i>Ḥāmās</i> (violence, injustice) is the word used for the wickedness that precipitated the flood (Gen&#160;6:11&#8211;13). Envy of the violent is its own form of moral corruption.</p>",
        "32": "<p>&#8220;For the LORD detests (<i>tôʿᵃbat-YHWH</i>) the devious (<i>naʿᵃlôz</i>).&#8221; <i>Tôʿēbāh</i> (abomination, what is detested) is one of the strongest negative assessment terms in Proverbs — it appears 22 times in the book, marking the most offensive transgressions (cf. 6:16&#8211;19; 11:1; 12:22). <i>Lûz</i> (to deviate, be crooked — cf. 2:15) defines the devious person. &#8220;But the upright (<i>yᵉšārîm</i>) are in his confidence (<i>sôdô</i>).&#8221; <i>Sôd</i> (intimate counsel, secret circle — the divine council, Ps&#160;25:14; Jer&#160;23:18; Amos&#160;3:7) — the upright are admitted to God&#8217;s inner circle.</p>",
        "33": "<p>&#8220;The LORD&#8217;s curse (<i>mᵉʾērat-YHWH</i>) rests on the house of the wicked, but he blesses (<i>yᵉbārek</i>) the home (<i>nᵉwēh</i>) of the righteous.&#8221; <i>Mᵉʾērāh</i> (curse) is the covenantal curse-word of Deuteronomy (Deut&#160;28:20; Mal&#160;2:2; 3:9). <i>Nāweh</i> (home, pasture, settled dwelling) suggests the home as a place of pastoral security. The contrast between cursed house and blessed home is the Deuteronomic two-ways applied to domestic life.</p>",
        "34": "<p>&#8220;He mocks the mockers (<i>lēṣîm yālîṣ</i>) himself, but shows favor (<i>ḥēn</i>) to the humble (<i>ʿᵃnāwîm</i>).&#8221; <i>Lêṣ</i> (mocker, scorner — cf. 1:22) is repaid in kind: God meets the scorner&#8217;s mockery with his own sovereign mockery (cf. Ps&#160;2:4). <i>ʿĀnāw</i> (humble, afflicted, meek — the socially low and spiritually receptive) receives <i>ḥēn</i> (grace, favor). This verse is directly quoted in Jas&#160;4:6 and 1&#160;Pet&#160;5:5 via the LXX, and is the fountainhead of the NT teaching on grace to the humble.</p>",
        "35": "<p>&#8220;The wise (<i>ḥᵃkāmîm</i>) will inherit (<i>yinḥᵃlû</i>) honor (<i>kābôd</i>), but fools (<i>kᵉsîlîm</i>) are left with disgrace (<i>mārîm qālôn</i>).&#8221; <i>Nāḥal</i> (to inherit as a lasting possession — the language of land-inheritance) applied to honor: wisdom&#8217;s honor is a permanent inheritance, not a temporary reputation. The contrast of <i>kābôd</i> (glory, weighty honor) with <i>qālôn</i> (shame, dishonor — the light and trivial) closes ch3&#8217;s positive portrait of wisdom with the two ultimate destinies: permanent honor or disgrace.</p>"
    }
}

existing = load_comm('mkt-original', 'proverbs')
merge_comm(existing, new_data)
save_comm('mkt-original', 'proverbs', existing)

for ch in sorted(new_data.keys(), key=int):
    vv = new_data[ch]
    have = sum(1 for v in vv if v in existing.get(ch, {}))
    print(f'  ch{ch}: {have}/{len(vv)} verses present')
